    heading: "Problems",
    body: "<p><strong>Problem 1.</strong> An electron oscillates at frequency $\\omega$. Using the Larmor formula, show that the radiated power scales as $\\omega^{4}$. How does this depend on wavelength?</p><p><strong>Problem 2.</strong> The ratio of Rayleigh scattering power for blue (400 nm) vs red (700 nm) light is about 9.4. Calculate this ratio for green (550 nm) vs red (700 nm) light.</p><p><strong>Problem 3.</strong> Explain why clouds are white while the sky is blue, using the concepts of Rayleigh and Mie scattering.</p><p><strong>Problem 4.</strong> A glass has index of refraction n = 1.52 at 400 nm and n = 1.50 at 700 nm. A beam of white light enters a prism with apex angle 60$^\\circ$ at minimum deviation. Estimate the angular spread between red and blue light exiting the prism.</p><p><strong>Problem 5.</strong> Why would a regular parallel wire cord catch fire if you tried to transmit a 1 GHz TV signal through it? Explain using the $\\omega^{4}$ dependence of radiated power.</p><p><strong>Problem 6.</strong> A microwave oven operates at 2.5 GHz. What is the wavelength? If the Faraday cage on the door has 1 cm spacing, explain why the microwaves don't escape but visible light does pass through.</p><p><strong>Problem 7.</strong> Using the microscopic model for the index of refraction, explain why n depends on frequency. What happens to n as $\\omega$ approaches the natural frequency $\\omega_{0}$ of the material?</p><p><strong>Problem 8.</strong> Derive Cauchy's formula n = A + B/$\\lambda^{2}$ from the expression n = 1 + $q^{2} \\rho$/(2$\\epsilon_{0}$m($\\omega_{0}^{2} - \\omega^{2}$)) in the limit $\\omega \\ll \\omega_{0}$.</p>",
